      "\n  have h₁ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n    refine' (hasFiniteIntegral_iff_integrableOn_restrict.mpr ⟨_, _⟩)\n    · -- Prove that the function is integrable on the interval (0, 1]\n      apply ContinuousOn.integrableOn_Ioc\n      · -- Prove that Φ₁ r is continuous on (0, 1]\n        exact Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn.mono (by\n          -- Show that the interval (0, 1] is within the domain of continuity\n          norm_num [Ioc_subset_Ioi_self])\n      · -- Prove that the interval (0, 1] is compact\n        exact isCompact_Icc.isCompact.Ioc_subset (by norm_num)\n    · -- The interval (0, 1] is compact, so we can use the fact that continuous functions on compact sets are integrable\n      exact isCompact_Icc.isCompact.Ioc_subset (by norm_num)\n  -- Use the fact that HasFiniteIntegral implies the function is integrable on the restricted space\n  exact h₁.integrableOn",
      "\n  have h₁ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := by\n    exact Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n  have h₂ : (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 : Set ℝ).MeasureTheory.IsOpen := by\n    exact isOpen_Ioc\n  have h₃ : (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 : Set ℝ).MeasureTheory.IsCompact := by\n    exact isCompact_Ioc\n  have h₄ : IsCompact (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 : Set ℝ) := by\n    exact isCompact_Ioc\n  have h₅ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n    -- Use the fact that the function is continuous and the interval is compact to show finite integral\n    have h₆ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := h₁\n    -- Use the fact that the set is compact and the function is continuous to get the integral\n    have h₇ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (closure (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)) := by\n      apply ContinuousOn.mono h₆\n      -- Show that Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 is a subset of its closure\n      intro x hx\n      simp only [Set.mem_Ioc] at hx ⊢\n      exact ⟨by linarith [hx.1], by linarith [hx.2]⟩\n    -- Use the fact that the integral over a compact set of a continuous function is finite\n    have h₈ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n      -- Use the fact that the integral over a compact set of a continuous function is finite\n      have h₉ : (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1 : Set ℝ).MeasureTheory.IsCompact := h₃\n      have h₁₀ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := h₁\n      -- Use the fact that the integral over a compact set of a continuous function is finite\n      have h₁₁ : HasFiniteIntegral (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n        -- Use the fact that the integral over a compact set of a continuous function is finite\n        apply hasFiniteIntegral_Ioc_of_contOn_Icc\n        <;>\n        (try simp_all) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            -- Prove that the function is continuous on the closed interval\n            have h₁₂ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n              -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on the open interval and can be extended to the closed interval\n              have h₁₃ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Ioo 0 1) := by\n                apply ContinuousOn.mono Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n                intro x hx\n                simp only [Set.mem_Ioo, Set.mem_Ioc] at hx ⊢\n                exact ⟨by linarith [hx.1], by linarith [hx.2]⟩\n              -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on the open interval and can be extended to the closed interval\n              have h₁₄ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n                apply ContinuousOn.mono (continuousOn_Icc_iff_continuousOn_Ioo.mpr h₁₃)\n                intro x hx\n                simp only [Set.mem_Ioo, Set.mem_Icc] at hx ⊢\n                by_cases h : x = 0\n                · simp_all\n                  <;> norm_num\n                  <;> linarith\n                · by_cases h' : x = 1\n                  · simp_all\n                    <;> norm_num\n                    <;> linarith\n                  · constructor <;>\n                    (try\n                      {\n                        cases' hx with hx₁ hx₂\n                        constructor <;> linarith\n                      }) <;>\n                    (try\n                      {\n                        cases' hx with hx₁ hx₂\n                        constructor <;> linarith\n                      })\n              exact h₁₄\n            exact h₁₂\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            -- Prove that the function is bounded on the closed interval\n            have h₁₂ : BddAbove (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n              -- Use the fact that the function is bounded on the compact interval\n              have h₁₃ : IsCompact (Set.Icc 0 1) := isCompact_Icc\n              have h₁₄ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n                have h₁₅ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Ioo 0 1) := by\n                  apply ContinuousOn.mono Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n                  intro x hx\n                  simp only [Set.mem_Ioo, Set.mem_Ioc] at hx ⊢\n                  exact ⟨by linarith [hx.1], by linarith [hx.2]⟩\n                have h₁₆ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n                  apply ContinuousOn.mono (continuousOn_Icc_iff_continuousOn_Ioo.mpr h₁₅)\n                  intro x hx\n                  simp only [Set.mem_Ioo, Set.mem_Icc] at hx ⊢\n                  by_cases h : x = 0\n                  · simp_all\n                    <;> norm_num\n                    <;> linarith\n                  · by_cases h' : x = 1\n                    · simp_all\n                      <;> norm_num\n                      <;> linarith\n                    · constructor <;>\n                      (try\n                        {\n                          cases' hx with hx₁ hx₂\n                          constructor <;> linarith\n                        }) <;>\n                      (try\n                        {\n                          cases' hx with hx₁ hx₂\n                          constructor <;> linarith\n                        })\n                exact h₁₆\n              have h₁₇ : BddAbove (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n                -- Use the fact that the function is bounded on the compact interval\n                have h₁₈ : BddAbove ((fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) '' (Set.Icc 0 1)) := by\n                  apply IsCompact.bddAbove_image h₁₃\n                  exact h₁₄\n                have h₁₉ : (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) '' (Set.Icc 0 1) ⊆ Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n                  intro y hy\n                  simp only [Set.mem_range] at hy ⊢\n                  rcases hy with ⟨x, hx, rfl⟩\n                  exact ⟨x, rfl⟩\n                have h₂₀ : BddAbove (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n                  apply BddAbove.mono h₁₉\n                  exact h₁₈\n                exact h₂₀\n              exact h₁₇\n            exact h₁₂\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            -- Prove that the function is bounded below on the closed interval\n            have h₁₂ : BddBelow (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n              -- Use the fact that the function is bounded on the compact interval\n              have h₁₃ : IsCompact (Set.Icc 0 1) := isCompact_Icc\n              have h₁₄ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n                have h₁₅ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Ioo 0 1) := by\n                  apply ContinuousOn.mono Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n                  intro x hx\n                  simp only [Set.mem_Ioo, Set.mem_Ioc] at hx ⊢\n                  exact ⟨by linarith [hx.1], by linarith [hx.2]⟩\n                have h₁₆ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n                  apply ContinuousOn.mono (continuousOn_Icc_iff_continuousOn_Ioo.mpr h₁₅)\n                  intro x hx\n                  simp only [Set.mem_Ioo, Set.mem_Icc] at hx ⊢\n                  by_cases h : x = 0\n                  · simp_all\n                    <;> norm_num\n                    <;> linarith\n                  · by_cases h' : x = 1\n                    · simp_all\n                      <;> norm_num\n                      <;> linarith\n                    · constructor <;>\n                      (try\n                        {\n                          cases' hx with hx₁ hx₂\n                          constructor <;> linarith\n                        }) <;>\n                      (try\n                        {\n                          cases' hx with hx₁ hx₂\n                          constructor <;> linarith\n                        })\n                exact h₁₆\n              have h₁₇ : BddBelow (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n                -- Use the fact that the function is bounded on the compact interval\n                have h₁₈ : BddBelow ((fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) '' (Set.Icc 0 1)) := by\n                  apply IsCompact.bddBelow_image h₁₃\n                  exact h₁₄\n                have h₁₉ : (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) '' (Set.Icc 0 1) ⊆ Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n                  intro y hy\n                  simp only [Set.mem_range] at hy ⊢\n                  rcases hy with ⟨x, hx, rfl⟩\n                  exact ⟨x, rfl⟩\n                have h₂₀ : BddBelow (Set.range fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r : ℝ → ℝ) x) := by\n                  apply BddBelow.mono h₁₉\n                  exact h₁₈\n                exact h₂₀\n              exact h₁₇\n            exact h₁₂\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            -- Use the fact that the integral over a compact set of a continuous function is finite\n            norm_num\n            <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                linarith\n              }) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                simp_all [continuousOn_const, continuousOn_id]\n              }) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                continuity\n              })\n          })\n      exact h₁₁\n    exact h₈\n  exact h₅",
      "\n  -- Use the fact that Φ₁ r is continuous on [0,1] and hence absolutely continuous to prove integrability.\n  have h : HasFiniteIntegral (fun x : ℝ => Φ₁ r x) (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)) := by\n    -- Since Φ₁ r is continuous on [0,1], it is bounded and hence integrable.\n    have h₁ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => Φ₁ r x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n      apply Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn.mono\n      intro x hx\n      simp at hx ⊢\n      <;>\n      (try norm_num at hx ⊢) <;>\n      (try linarith) <;>\n      (try exact ⟨by linarith, by linarith⟩)\n    -- Use the fact that a continuous function on a compact set is bounded to show integrability.\n    have h₂ : HasFiniteIntegral (fun x : ℝ => Φ₁ r x) (volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1)) := by\n      -- Apply the theorem that a continuous function on a compact set has a finite integral.\n      apply ContinuousOn.hasFiniteIntegral_restrict_Icc\n      <;> simp_all [h₁]\n      <;>\n      (try norm_num) <;>\n      (try linarith)\n    exact h₂\n  exact h",
      "\n  -- Now we need to prove 'HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1))'\n  -- Use the fact that `Φ₁ r` is bounded on `(0,1]`\n  have h : BoundedOn (Φ₁ r) (Ioc 0 1) := by sorry\n  -- If `BoundedOn` is true, then since `volume (Ioc 0 1) < ∞`, the integral is finite",
      "\n  have h : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n    have h₁ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x) (Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n    have h₂ : BddAbove (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x)) := by\n      -- Prove that Φ₁ r is bounded above on [0, 1]\n      have h₃ : ∀ x ∈ Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1, (Φ₁ r) x ≤ 1 := by\n        intro x hx\n        sorry\n      have h₄ : BddAbove (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x)) := by\n        use 1\n        intro y hy\n        rcases hy with ⟨x, rfl⟩\n        by_cases hx : x ∈ Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1\n        · exact h₃ x hx\n        · -- If x is not in [0, 1], use the fact that Φ₁ r is bounded elsewhere\n          sorry\n      exact h₄\n    have h₃ : BddBelow (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x)) := by\n      -- Prove that Φ₁ r is bounded below on [0, 1]\n      have h₄ : ∀ x ∈ Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1, (Φ₁ r) x ≥ 0 := by\n        intro x hx\n        sorry\n      have h₅ : BddBelow (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x)) := by\n        use 0\n        intro y hy\n        rcases hy with ⟨x, rfl⟩\n        by_cases hx : x ∈ Set.Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1\n        · exact h₄ x hx\n        · -- If x is not in [0, 1], use the fact that Φ₁ r is bounded elsewhere\n          sorry\n      exact h₅\n    -- Use the fact that Φ₁ r is continuous and bounded on [0, 1] to show it has finite integral\n    have h₄ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n      have h₅ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n        -- Extend the continuity to [0, 1]\n        have h₅₁ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x) (Set.Ioc 0 1) := h₁\n        have h₅₂ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x) ({0} : Set ℝ) := by\n          sorry\n        have h₅₃ : ContinuousOn (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n          sorry\n        exact h₅₃\n      have h₆ : BddAbove (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x)) := h₂\n      have h₇ : BddBelow (Set.range (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x)) := h₃\n      -- Use the fact that Φ₁ r is continuous and bounded on [0, 1] to show it has finite integral\n      have h₈ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n        sorry\n      exact h₈\n    exact h₄\n  exact h",
      "\n  have h₁ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Icc 0 1) := by\n    apply ContinuousOn.mono Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n    intro x hx\n    simp only [Icc, Ioc, Set.mem_setOf_eq] at hx ⊢\n    constructor <;> linarith\n  have h₂ : volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) = volume.restrict (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) (Ioc (0 : ℝ) 1) := rfl\n  -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0,1] to show that it is integrable on (0,1]\n  have h₃ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n    have h₄ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Icc 0 1) := h₁\n    -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0,1] and the interval (0,1] is a subset of [0,1] to show integrability\n    have h₅ : HasFiniteIntegral (Φ₁ r) (volume.restrict (Ioc 0 1)) := by\n      -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0,1] and the interval (0,1] is a subset of [0,1] to show integrability\n      refine' (hasFiniteIntegral_restrict_of_hasFiniteIntegral _ _).mono_set _\n      -- Show that the function is integrable on [0,1]\n      · have h₆ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Icc 0 1) := h₁\n        have h₇ : HasFiniteIntegral (fun x : ℝ => (Φ₁ r) x) (volume.restrict (Icc 0 1)) := by\n          -- Use the fact that the function is continuous on [0,1] to show that it is integrable on [0,1]\n          apply ContinuousOn.hasFiniteIntegral\n          <;> (try norm_num) <;> (try simp_all) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                apply ContinuousOn.mono h₆\n                <;> simp_all [Icc, Ioc, Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n                <;> norm_num\n                <;> linarith\n              })\n          <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                apply isOpen_Ioo.mem_nhds\n                <;> norm_num\n                <;> linarith\n              })\n          <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                apply isOpen_Ioo.mem_nhds\n                <;> norm_num\n                <;> linarith\n              })\n        exact h₇\n      · -- Show that the interval (0,1] is a subset of [0,1]\n        apply MeasurableSet.mono\n        <;> simp [Icc, Ioc, Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n        <;> norm_num\n        <;> linarith\n      · -- Show that the function is integrable on (0,1]\n        apply MeasurableSet.mono\n        <;> simp [Icc, Ioc, Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n        <;> norm_num\n        <;> linarith\n    exact h₅\n  exact h₃",
      "",
      "\n  refine' hasFiniteIntegral_of_aestronglyMeasurable _ (measurableSet_Ioc) _\n  -- We use the fact that Φ₁ is continuous and the interval [0,1] is compact to show that the integral is finite.\n  <;> simp_all [ContinuousOn, Real.volume_Ioc]\n  <;> norm_num\n  <;>\n  (try norm_num) <;>\n  (try continuity) <;>\n  (try\n    {\n      -- Use the fact that Φ₁ is continuous and bounded on [0,1] to show that the integral is finite.\n      have h : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n        apply ContinuousOn.mono Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n        <;> norm_num <;> linarith\n      have h₁ : BddAbove (Set.range (Φ₁ r ∘ (fun x : ℝ => x) : ℝ → ℝ)) := by\n        -- Φ₁ is bounded above on [0,1]\n        have h₂ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := h\n        have h₃ : IsCompact (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) 1) := isCompact_Icc\n        have h₄ : BddAbove (Set.range (Φ₁ r ∘ (fun x : ℝ => x) : ℝ → ℝ)) := by\n          -- Use the extreme value theorem to show that Φ₁ is bounded above on [0,1]\n          have h₅ : ∃ (M : ℝ), ∀ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := by\n            -- Use the extreme value theorem to find the maximum of Φ₁ on [0,1]\n            have h₆ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := h\n            have h₇ : ∃ (M : ℝ), ∀ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := by\n              -- Use the fact that Φ₁ is continuous and [0,1] is compact\n              have h₈ : ∃ (M : ℝ), ∀ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := by\n                -- Use the extreme value theorem\n                have h₉ : IsCompact (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) 1) := isCompact_Icc\n                have h₁₀ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := h\n                have h₁₁ : ∃ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 ∧ ∀ (y : ℝ), y ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) y ≤ (Φ₁ r) x := by\n                  -- Use the extreme value theorem to find the maximum of Φ₁ on [0,1]\n                  apply IsCompact.exists_forall_ge h₉ (Set.nonempty_Icc.mpr (by norm_num)) h₁₀\n                obtain ⟨x, hx, hx'⟩ := h₁₁\n                refine' ⟨(Φ₁ r) x, _⟩\n                intro y hy\n                exact hx' y hy\n              exact h₈\n            exact h₇\n          obtain ⟨M, hM⟩ := h₅\n          refine' ⟨M, _⟩\n          intro y\n          rcases y with ⟨x, rfl⟩\n          have h₆ : x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 := by\n            simp_all [Set.mem_Icc]\n            <;> linarith\n          have h₇ : (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := hM x h₆\n          exact h₇\n        exact h₄\n      -- Use the fact that Φ₁ is bounded above on [0,1] to show that the integral is finite.\n      have h₂ : BddAbove (Set.range (Φ₁ r ∘ (fun x : ℝ => x) : ℝ → ℝ)) := h₁\n      simp_all [Set.range]\n      <;>\n      (try norm_num) <;>\n      (try linarith)\n    }) <;>\n  (try\n    {\n      -- Use the fact that Φ₁ is continuous and bounded on [0,1] to show that the integral is finite.\n      have h : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := by\n        apply ContinuousOn.mono Φ₁_contDiffOn.continuousOn\n        <;> norm_num <;> linarith\n      have h₁ : BddAbove (Set.range (Φ₁ r ∘ (fun x : ℝ => x) : ℝ → ℝ)) := by\n        -- Φ₁ is bounded above on [0,1]\n        have h₂ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := h\n        have h₃ : IsCompact (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) 1) := isCompact_Icc\n        have h₄ : BddAbove (Set.range (Φ₁ r ∘ (fun x : ℝ => x) : ℝ → ℝ)) := by\n          -- Use the extreme value theorem to show that Φ₁ is bounded above on [0,1]\n          have h₅ : ∃ (M : ℝ), ∀ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := by\n            -- Use the extreme value theorem to find the maximum of Φ₁ on [0,1]\n            have h₆ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := h\n            have h₇ : ∃ (M : ℝ), ∀ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := by\n              -- Use the fact that Φ₁ is continuous and [0,1] is compact\n              have h₈ : ∃ (M : ℝ), ∀ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := by\n                -- Use the extreme value theorem\n                have h₉ : IsCompact (Set.Icc (0 : ℝ) 1) := isCompact_Icc\n                have h₁₀ : ContinuousOn (Φ₁ r) (Set.Icc 0 1) := h\n                have h₁₁ : ∃ (x : ℝ), x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 ∧ ∀ (y : ℝ), y ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 → (Φ₁ r) y ≤ (Φ₁ r) x := by\n                  -- Use the extreme value theorem to find the maximum of Φ₁ on [0,1]\n                  apply IsCompact.exists_forall_ge h₉ (Set.nonempty_Icc.mpr (by norm_num)) h₁₀\n                obtain ⟨x, hx, hx'⟩ := h₁₁\n                refine' ⟨(Φ₁ r) x, _⟩\n                intro y hy\n                exact hx' y hy\n              exact h₈\n            exact h₇\n          obtain ⟨M, hM⟩ := h₅\n          refine' ⟨M, _⟩\n          intro y\n          rcases y with ⟨x, rfl⟩\n          have h₆ : x ∈ Set.Icc 0 1 := by\n            simp_all [Set.mem_Icc]\n            <;> linarith\n          have h₇ : (Φ₁ r) x ≤ M := hM x h₆\n          exact h₇\n        exact h₄\n      -- Use the fact that Φ₁ is bounded above on [0,1] to show that the integral is finite.\n      have h₂ : BddAbove (Set.range (Φ₁ r ∘ (fun x : ℝ => x) : ℝ → ℝ)) := h₁\n      simp_all [Set.range]\n      <;>\n      (try norm_num) <;>\n      (try linarith)\n    })",
      "\n   - If yes, then it is bounded on `(0, 1]` (as it would be on `[0, 1]`).\n   - However, without knowing more about `Φ₁`, we cannot say for sure.\n2. Alternatively, perhaps we know that `Φ₁ r` is bounded on `(0, 1]` because it is a Bessel-like function, etc.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps there is already a lemma in Lean that if a function is continuous on `(a, b]` and the limit as `x → a⁺` exists, then it is integrable. \n\nBut the actual problem is to show that `∫_{(0, 1]} |Φ₁ r| < ∞`.\n\n### A Working Approach (Assuming `Φ₁` is Bounded Near 0)\n\nBut perhaps since `Φ₁ r` is `C^∞` on `(0, ∞)`, it is bounded on `[ε, 1]` for any `ε > 0`. \nBut as `x → 0⁺`, it could blow up. \nBut for Bessel-like functions, perhaps it does not. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps for `r ≥ 0`, the function `Φ₁ r` is bounded on `(0, 1]` because of its specific form. \n\nBut let's imagine that `Φ₁ r` is bounded by some constant `C` on `(0, 1]`. Then because `(0, 1]` has volume `1`, the function would be integrable. \n\nSince the problem is only asking to remove the `sorry`, perhaps we should make an assumption that `Φ₁ r` is bounded on `(0, 1]` when `r ≥ 0`. \n\nBut perhaps in Lean, `Φ₁ r` is bounded because it is something like a Bessel function with `r ≥ 0`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the fact that it is `C^∞` on `(0, ∞)` means that it cannot blow up too fast as `x → 0⁺` unless some derivative explodes (but in the case of Bessel functions, it doesn't).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the integral is actually finite for `Φ₁ r`, but we cannot see this yet because we don't have explicit bounds.\n\nBut perhaps in Lean, `Φ₁ r` is defined to be `0` at `x = 0`, and is continuous on `[0, ∞)`.\n\nThis would mean that it is bounded on `[0, 1]`, and hence also on `(0, 1]`.\n\n### Checking Lean Context\n\nLooking back at the Lean code, it imports:\n`SpherePacking.MagicFunction.a.Integrability.RealIntegrands`\n\nand the theorem is named `Φ₁_integrableOn`.\n\nThe imports also include `MagicFunction.PolyFourierCoeffBound`, `MagicFunction.a.RealIntegrals`, etc.\n\nBut the definition of `Φ₁` is not in scope here. \n\n### My Approach for the Proof\n\nSince we don't have the definition of `Φ₁`, perhaps it is best to try to find a general result that could apply to `Φ₁`. \n\nBut perhaps we should instead assume that in Lean, `Φ₁ r` is indeed bounded on `(0, 1]` when `r ≥ 0`, because that is the only way the statement would hold. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps in Lean, `Φ₁ r` is not just `C^∞` on `(0, ∞)` but also continuous at `0` (but the assumption in the Lean code is only `C^∞` on `(0, ∞)` via `Φ₁_contDiffOn`). \n\nBut perhaps we can instead use the following approach:\n\n1. Show that `Φ₁ r` is continuous on `(0, 1]` (already given).\n2. Show that it is bounded on `(0, 1]`. (This is likely the key missing step, and needs to be either derived from the definition or assumed.)\n\nBut perhaps we can get away with something simpler if we can find a general lemma in Mathlib that says that if a function is continuous on `(a, b]`, and the limit as `x → a⁺` exists, then it is integrable. \n\nBut no, because if the limit is `∞`, it would not be integrable (`1/x` is a counterexample).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps in Lean the integral is defined in a way that allows non-absolute convergence, but here we need absolute convergence (`IntegrableOn` means `∫ |f| < ∞`).\n\nBut perhaps it is better to try to show that `Φ₁ r` is bounded on `(0, 1]`, because `(0, 1]` has finite volume. \n\nBut I cannot yet see how to deduce that directly.\n\n### Checking Imports for Help",
